</think>

Biographies of Zhang Shizhi and Feng Tang
Zhang, the Minister of Justice, named Shizhi, was a native of Duyang, with the courtesy name Ji. He had an elder brother named Zhong, who lived with him. Zhong served as a cavalry attendant, attending Emperor Wen, but after ten years he received no promotion and remained unknown. Shizhi said: "Having served long in office has diminished my brother's estate, without success." He wished to resign and return home. Yuan Ao, a commandant of the central regiment, knowing his worth and regretting his departure, requested that Shizhi be transferred to the position of gentleman attendant. After Shizhi had attended court, he then stepped forward to speak on suitable matters. Emperor Wen said: "Do not be overly lofty in your discourse; let what is said be practicable now." Thus Shizhi spoke of the affairs between Qin and Han, of why Qin had fallen and Han had risen, at length. Emperor Wen praised him and appointed Shizhi as gentleman attendant-in-waiting.
Shizhi accompanied the emperor on a tour, ascending the tiger enclosure. The emperor asked the commandant of the Upper Park about the register of birds and beasts, posing more than ten questions. The commandant looked left and right, unable to answer any. The keeper of the tiger enclosure, standing nearby, answered in the commandant's place, giving a detailed account of the register of birds and beasts the emperor had asked about, wishing to observe his ability to respond fluently and endlessly. Emperor Wen said: "Should an official not be like this? The commandant is worthless!" He then ordered Shizhi to appoint the keeper as commandant of the Upper Park. Shizhi had long before said: "Your Majesty, what kind of man is the Marquis of Jiang, Zhou Bo?" The emperor replied: "He is an elder." He then asked again: "What kind of man is the Marquis of Dongyang, Zhang Xiang?" The emperor again replied: "He is an elder." Shizhi said: "The Marquis of Jiang and the Marquis of Dongyang are called elders, yet these two men, when speaking, cannot even utter a word—how could this keeper, with his glib tongue and ready speech, be superior? Moreover, Qin relied on clerks of brush and tablet, officials vying with each other in strictness and meticulousness, yet their harm was merely formalism, lacking genuine benevolence. Hence their faults went unnoticed, and they declined until the reign of the Second Emperor, when the empire collapsed. Now Your Majesty promotes the keeper for his eloquence; I fear the world will follow the wind, vying for eloquence without substance. Furthermore, the inferior follow the superior as swiftly as echo and shadow; policies must be examined carefully." Emperor Wen said: "Good." He then ceased the appointment of the keeper.
The emperor entered his carriage, summoned Shizhi to ride beside him, proceeded slowly, and asked Shizhi about the faults of Qin. Shizhi explained them fully. Upon reaching the palace, the emperor appointed Shizhi as commandant of the gentlemen-attendants.
Soon after, the crown prince and the King of Liang rode together in a carriage to attend court, not dismounting at the Sima Gate. Thus Shizhi followed and stopped the crown prince and the King of Liang, forbidding them from entering the palace gate. He then impeached them for failing to dismount at the public gate, showing disrespect, and memorialized the matter. Empress Dowager Bo heard of it; Emperor Wen, removing his hat, apologized: "I have not taught my son properly." Empress Dowager Bo then sent an envoy with an edict to pardon the crown prince and the King of Liang, after which they were allowed to enter. From this, Emperor Wen regarded Shizhi as extraordinary and appointed him as a grand master.
Soon after, he became a commandant of the central regiment. On a tour to the Mausoleum of Ba, he resided north of the latrine. At this time, Consort Shen accompanied him; the emperor pointed out to Consort Shen the new road to Xin Feng, saying: "This is the road to Handan." He ordered Consort Shen to play the se, and he himself leaned against the se and sang, his feelings bleak and sorrowful. He turned to the ministers and said: "Alas! To make a coffin of stone from the northern mountains, to use hemp and silk to pad it, to lacquer it with black lacquer—could it possibly be moved?" All present said: "Good." Shizhi then stepped forward and said: "If within it there is something desirable, even if sealed by the southern mountains, there would still be a flaw; if within it there is nothing desirable, even without a stone coffin, what grief would there be?" Emperor Wen praised him. Later, he appointed Shizhi as Minister of Justice.
Soon after, the emperor went out from the middle Wei Bridge, when a man ran out from beneath the bridge, startling the imperial carriage and horses. The emperor then ordered cavalry to seize him, assigning the case to the Minister of Justice. Shizhi investigated and questioned. The man said: "I am a county man; I heard the clearing of the road, hid beneath the bridge. After a while, thinking the procession had passed, I came out and saw the imperial carriage and cavalry, and fled." The Minister of Justice Qin Dang judged: one person who had violated the road-clearing edict should be fined. Emperor Wen became angry and said: "This man startled my horse; my horse relied on its gentleness; if it had been another horse, would it not have surely harmed me? And yet the Minister of Justice fines him only!" Shizhi said: "The law is what the Son of Heaven shares with the world. Now the law is as such, yet you would increase it—this makes the law untrustworthy to the people. Moreover, at that time, if the emperor had ordered immediate execution, it would have been done. But now, after referring the case to the Minister of Justice, the Minister of Justice is the equity of the world; one tilt and the whole world applies the law with varying severity—where would the people place their hands and feet? Only Your Majesty should consider this." After a long while, the emperor said: "The Minister of Justice is correct."
Later, someone stole a jade ring from before the seat in the Gao Temple; he was captured, and Emperor Wen, enraged, referred the case to the Minister of Justice for judgment. Shizhi, according to the law, found that one who steals objects used in the ancestral temple should be memorialized, and the memorial prescribed abandonment in the market. Emperor Wen flew into a rage and said: "How devoid of morality can one be, to steal the vessels of the former emperor's temple? We, who serve as Minister of Justice, wish to punish him by extermination of his clan, yet you memorialize him according to the law—this is not how we should jointly uphold the intent of the ancestral temple." Shizhi removed his hat, bowed his head to the ground, and apologized: "The law as it stands is sufficient. Moreover, though the guilt is equal, distinction is made between rebellion and obedience. Now, if one steals the vessels of the ancestral temple and is exterminated, it is as if one in ten thousand; suppose a foolish man takes a handful of earth from the Changling mausoleum—how would Your Majesty increase the law against him?" After a long time, Emperor Wen discussed it with Empress Dowager Bo, and then allowed the Minister of Justice's judgment to stand. At that time, the commandant of the cavalry, Marquis Zhou Yafu, and the Chancellor of Liang, Marquis Wang Tian of Shandu, met Shizhi and held discussions on equity, thus becoming close friends. Minister of Justice Zhang thus gained fame throughout the world.
After Emperor Wen died, Emperor Jing ascended the throne; Shizhi feared, claimed illness, wished to resign and depart, yet dreaded a great punishment; he wished to apologize, yet did not know how. Following the plan of Wang Sheng, he finally apologized, and Emperor Jing took no further action.
Wang Sheng was skilled in Huang-Lao discourse, a recluse. He had once been summoned to reside in the court; the Three Dukes and Nine Ministers all gathered and stood. Wang Sheng, an old man, said: "My sandal strap has come loose," and, turning to Minister of Justice Zhang, said: "Tie my sandal strap for me!" Shizhi knelt and tied it. Afterward, someone said to Wang Sheng: "How can you alone, in court, humiliate Minister of Justice Zhang, making him kneel to tie your sandal strap?" Wang Sheng replied: "I am old and lowly; I estimate that I can bring no benefit to Minister of Justice Zhang. Minister of Justice Zhang is today a renowned minister of the world; I therefore slightly humiliate him, making him kneel to tie my sandal strap, in order to increase his stature." The dukes heard this, esteemed Wang Sheng, and held Minister of Justice Zhang in high regard.
Minister of Justice Zhang served Emperor Jing for over a year, then became Chancellor of the Huainan King, still holding to his past conduct. After a long time, Shizhi died. His son was named Zhang Zhi, with the courtesy name Changgong; he reached the rank of grand master, then was dismissed. Because he could not conform to the customs of the age, he never held office throughout his life.
Feng Tang's grandfather was a man of Zhao; his father moved to Dai. After the founding of Han, they moved to Anling. Tang became known for filial piety, served as chief of the middle regiment attendants, and attended Emperor Wen. Emperor Wen, traveling in his carriage, asked Tang: "Old sir, why did you become an attendant? Where is your home?" Tang answered truthfully. Emperor Wen said: "When I resided in Dai, my food supervisor Gao Ju often told me of the excellence of the Zhao general Li Qi, who fought beneath Julu. Now, whenever I eat, my thoughts never fail to be at Julu. Do you know this?" Tang replied: "He is still not equal to Lian Po and Li Mu as generals." The emperor asked: "Why?" Tang said: "My grandfather, when in Zhao, served as an officer (properly) [commander] of troops, good friends with Li Mu. My father therefore served as Chancellor of Dai, good friends with the Zhao general Li Qi, knowing his character." After the emperor heard of Lian Po and Li Mu's character, he was greatly pleased, and slapped his thigh, saying: "Alas! I alone did not obtain Lian Po and Li Mu as my generals; otherwise, I would not have worried about the Xiongnu!" Tang said: "Your Majesty! Even if you obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you would not be able to use them." The emperor grew angry, rose, and entered the inner chambers. After a long while, he summoned Tang and rebuked him: "How dare you, in public, humiliate me, with no private place?" Tang apologized: "I am a rustic man, unaware of taboos."
At that time, the Xiongnu had recently made a great incursion into Chao-na, killing the commandant of Beidi, Gong. The emperor, thinking of the Hu invaders, then, after a long while, again asked Tang: "How do you know that I cannot use Lian Po and Li Mu?" Tang replied: "I have heard that in ancient times, when kings dispatched generals, they knelt and pushed the chariot's yoke, saying: 'Within the frontier, I command; beyond the frontier, the general commands.' Military merit, rank, and rewards are all decided outside; upon return, they memorialize. This is not empty talk. My grandfather said: Li Mu, as general of Zhao guarding the frontier, used the market taxes of the army to personally feed and reward the troops, deciding rewards externally, not disturbed from within. Entrusting them and demanding success, thus Li Mu was able to fully employ his wisdom and ability, dispatching selected chariots numbering 1,300, crossbowmen numbering 13,000, and warriors worth a hundred gold numbering 100,000; thus he pursued the Chanyu northward, destroyed the Eastern Hu, exterminated the Dan Lin, westward suppressed the strong Qin, and southward supported Han and Wei. At that time, Zhao was nearly hegemonic. Later, when Zhao King Qian ascended the throne, his mother was an actress. King Qian ascended, then used Guo Kai's slander, and ultimately executed Li Mu, ordering Yan Ju to replace him. Thus the troops were defeated in the north, falling into Qin's capture and destruction. Now I have privately heard that Wei Shang, as commandant of Yunzhong, used the market taxes of his army entirely to feed and reward the soldiers, [expended] private funds, every five days slaughtering an ox to entertain guests, military officers, and attendants; thus the Xiongnu kept far away, not approaching the Yunzhong frontier. The barbarians once entered; Wei Shang then led chariots and cavalry to attack them, killing many of their number. For the soldiers are all sons of families, rising from the fields to join the army, knowing neither register nor symbol. They fight all day, beheading and capturing the enemy, reporting merit to the office, yet a single word does not correspond; the civil officials bind them with law. Their rewards are not carried out, while officials uphold the law and must apply it. I humbly believe that Your Majesty's law is too clear, rewards too light, punishments too heavy. Moreover, the commandant of Yunzhong, Wei Shang, was punished by having his rank reduced and sentenced to labor for having reported enemy beheads short by six levels; Your Majesty handed him over to officials, who stripped his rank and fined him to labor. From this, even if Your Majesty obtained Lian Po and Li Mu, you would not be able to use them. I truly am foolish, have touched upon taboos, guilty of death, guilty of death!" Emperor Wen was pleased. That day he ordered Feng Tang to carry the ceremonial baton to pardon Wei Shang, restore him as commandant of Yunzhong, and appointed Tang as commandant of cavalry and chariots, overseeing the commandant of cavalry and chariots and the vehicles and soldiers of the commanderies and states.
Seven years later, Emperor Jing ascended the throne and appointed Tang as Chancellor of Chu, then dismissed him. Emperor Wu ascended the throne, sought worthy men, and recommended Feng Tang. Tang was then over ninety years old, unable to resume office, so he had his son Feng Sui serve as an attendant. Sui bore the courtesy name Wangsun; he too was an extraordinary man, and was on good terms with me.
The Grand Historian said: Zhang Ji's words about elders—upholding the law without flattery—Feng Gong's discussion on commanders and leaders—is truly flavorful! Truly flavorful! As the saying goes: 'Not knowing the man, observe his friends.' The praises of these two lords can be inscribed in the halls of court. The Book says: 'Not partial, not partisan, the king's way is vast and vast; not partisan, not partial, the king's way is convenient and convenient.' Zhang Ji and Feng Gong approach this. [end of text]


